  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Money laundering is a serious federal offense in the United States, and the penalties can be severe. Under Title 18, U.S. Code, Section 1956 and Section 1957, the penalties for money laundering include:\n\n1. **Imprisonment**: Individuals convicted of money laundering can face up to **20 years in federal prison** per count. If the offense involves proceeds from certain specified unlawful activities (e.g., drug trafficking or terrorism), the maximum sentence can increase.\n\n2. **Fines**: The court may impose fines of up to **$500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds**, whichever is greater. For businesses or organizations, fines can reach up to **$1 million or twice the value of the laundered funds**.\n\n3. **Asset Forfeiture**: The government can seize and forfeit any property, funds, or assets involved in or derived from the money laundering activity.\n\n4. **Supervised Release**: In addition to imprisonment, offenders may be placed on **supervised release** for up to **3 years** after serving their prison sentence.\n\n5. **Enhanced Penalties**: Certain aggravating factors, such as involvement in large-scale or international money laundering schemes, can lead to enhanced penalties.\n\nAdditionally, money laundering charges are often brought alongside other criminal charges (e.g., fraud, drug trafficking, or racketeering), which can result in cumulative penalties. The specific penalties depend on the facts of the case, the amount of money involved, and the defendant\u2019s criminal history.",
